A 114-year-old patient was among the 1,546 new COVID-19 infections announced from a sample of 9,752 people tested in the last one day This is according to a press statement issued by the Ministry of Health on Thursday. The new infections which represent a positivity rate of 15.9 percent push the total number of confirmed cases to 217,276. “From the cases 1,531 are Kenyans while 15 are foreigners. 783 females while 763 are males,” the Health Ministry said on Thursday “The youngest is a two-month-old infant while the oldest is 114 years,” Kenya has tested 2,228,318 samples so far. Nairobi led with the highest infections, a week in a row, as per the Ministry data, posting 517 cases on Thursday. Also Read: Kiambu and Nyeri followed suit, posting 142 and 106 new infections. Across the rest of the country, the new infections are distributed as follows: Makueni 88, Machakos 81, Nakuru 76, Mombasa 68, Kilifi 54, Kajiado 45, Murang’a 41, Uasin Gishu 33, Kirinyaga 31,Nyandarua 28, Busia 18,Trans Nzoia 16, Kitui 16, Kisii 15, Baringo 15, Embu 15, Marsabit 15, Lamu 14, Vihiga 12, Tharaka Nithi 10, Siaya 9, Nandi 8, Garissa 8, Taita Taveta 7, Kakamega 7, Tana River 6, Kwale 6, West Pokot 6, Kericho 5, Elgeyo Marakwet 4, Samburu 4, Kisumu 3, Bungoma 3, Homa Bay, Isiolo, Laikipia, Meru, Narok and Turkana 2 cases each, Bomet 1 and Migori 1. A total of 1,929 patients are currently admitted in various health facilities countrywide, while 9,043 are under the Home-Based Isolation and Care program. Meanwhile, Kenya reported 559 new recoveries on Thursday, pushing the total number of recoveries so far to 199,998. “439 recoveries were from the Home-Based Isolation and Care program while 120 are from various health facilities countrywide,” the Health Ministry said. At the same time, the death toll from the disease has hit 4,273 following a report of 32 new deaths. “32 patients have succumbed to the disease, one of them having occurred in the last 24 hours while 31 are late deaths reported after conducting facility record audits on diverse dates in the months of April, May, June, July and August 2021,” the Health Ministry added. Video Of The Day: KEMRI scientists examine safety of anti-malarial drugs in first trimester of pregnancy